    <fr:title text="Cardinality of the set of partial functions › "><fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KE.xml" title="Cardinality of the set of partial functions" addr="jms-00KE" type="local">Cardinality of the set of <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">partial functions</fr:link></fr:link> › </fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:p>A partial function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } B]]></fr:tex> associates to each element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> either a unique element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a\right )\mathclose {}}\in  B]]></fr:tex> when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a\right )\mathclose {}}{\downarrow }]]></fr:tex>, or it associates nothing. Therefore, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{A}]]></fr:tex> many possibilities, each followed by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{B}+1]]></fr:tex> many possibilities.</html:p>
</fr:mainmatter>
